  "example_section_data": {
    "children": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "First we generate some random data from a Weibull distribution\nwith shape parameter 2.5, and plot the histogram of the data:"
      },
      {
        "type": "code",
        "value": "import numpy as np\nfrom scipy import stats\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nrng = np.random.default_rng()\nc = 2.5\nx = stats.weibull_min.rvs(c, scale=4, size=2000, random_state=rng)"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "Take a look at the histogram of the data."
      },
      {
        "type": "code",
        "value": "fig1, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 4))\nax.hist(x, bins=50)\nax.set_title('Histogram of x')\nplt.show()"
      },
      {
        "type": "Fig",
        "value": {
          "kind": "assets",
          "module": "scipy",
          "path": "fig-scipy.stats._morestats:ppcc_plot-0-840be1c1.png",
          "type": "RefInfo",
          "version": "1.10.1"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "Now we explore this data with a PPCC plot as well as the related\nprobability plot and Box-Cox normplot.  A red line is drawn where we\nexpect the PPCC value to be maximal (at the shape parameter ``c``\nused above):"
      },
      {
        "type": "code",
        "value": "fig2 = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))\nax1 = fig2.add_subplot(1, 3, 1)\nax2 = fig2.add_subplot(1, 3, 2)\nax3 = fig2.add_subplot(1, 3, 3)\nres = stats.probplot(x, plot=ax1)\nres = stats.boxcox_normplot(x, -4, 4, plot=ax2)\nres = stats.ppcc_plot(x, c/2, 2*c, dist='weibull_min', plot=ax3)\nax3.axvline(c, color='r')\nplt.show()"
      },
      {
        "type": "Fig",
        "value": {
          "kind": "assets",
